<HEADLINE>
<P>
ERMA BOMBECK: UNDERCUTTING THANKSGIVING CARVING CHORE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERMA BOMBECK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ever since Phyllis Diller balanced her turkey on a window ledge and stuffed it 
through the beak, this traditional bird has been an enigma to cooks everywhere. 
</P>
<P>
We are intimidated by its size. (You could lose your luggage in there.) We are 
awed by its history and threatened by its independence. ("We'll be done when we 
say we're done!") 
</P>
<P>
I cannot look at a pale, naked turkey with its thunder thighs, sunken chest and 
accordion neck without thinking, "I have seen my future and you are it!" It's 
unsettling to me. It is obviously the resemblance that has prompted my mother 
every year to call, "Erma, time for you to carve the turkey." 
</P>
<P>
I have no idea how I got stuck with this dubious honor. After 40 years of 
marriage, I still haven't a clue as to how to cut up a whole chicken. We call 
them mystery parts. Anyone who can identify where they belong wins a big prize. 
</P>
<P>
But back to the turkey. I approach the bronze bird like a sumo wrestler 
circling his opponent to find out where his weaknesses and strengths are. Then 
I begin. We're not talking Norman Rockwell here. It's more like a chain-saw 
massacre. If the legs don't fall off in my hands, my mother is lamenting, "It's 
not done yet, is it?" If they do fall off in my hands, my father says, "It's 
overcooked. It'll be dry." 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, my husband hovers over me and predicts, "You are going to cut 
yourself." I have always wanted to answer him, "You have just ruined my 
surprise!" 
</P>
<P>
I've tried studying all those little charts that are put out just before the 
holidays, the ones that tell you where to make the incisions that leave you 
with a wall of white meat that slides off in thin slices. It never works for 
me. 
</P>
<P>
Usually I resort to a list of things to blame for the miserable mound of meat 
on the platter: The knife was dull; the light was burned out over the stove; 
the turkey was too hot when I carved it/too cold when I carved it; the 
Republicans did something; nuclear testing is at work; glasnost . . . take your 
pick. 
</P>
<P>
Today will be no different than Thanksgivings past. I will once again 
arm-wrestle a 20-pound bird to the platter and under-whelm everyone. But as in 
the past, I will allow myself a few minutes to reflect on how simple life would 
have been if the Pilgrims had just tossed up a salad and thrown a few steaks on 
the grill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA112389-0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 138554 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 23, 1989, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
