<HEADLINE>
<P>
10 LIVELY SPOTS; 
</P>
<P>
FOLK DANCING GROUPS CELEBRATE A WORLD OF TRADITION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LYNN STOKES, Stokes is a free-lance writer. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Folk dancing, popular in the '60s along with coffeehouses and guitars, has 
survived the '80s and is marching boldly into the '90s. 
</P>
<P>
Broadly defined, folk dancing is the traditional 
</P>
<P>
dance form of a country or a particular ethnic group. The ever-faster hora 
danced at a bar mitzvah, the whirling polkas at a Polish wedding, the line 
dance in "Zorba the Greek" -- all are folk dances. 
</P>
<P>
Some dances are for couples only, others take all comers. In some the dancers 
are arranged in squares, in others they form circles or lines. The variations 
are as endless as the various peoples and cultures of the world. 
</P>
<P>
Here are some folk dancing places in the Los Angeles area. 
</P>
<P>
Westwood Co-Op Folk Dancers -- Thursday nights. Emerson Junior High Gymnasium, 
1650 N. Selby Ave., West Los Angeles. Beginners class in international dancing 
from 7:30 to 9 p.m., intermediate and advanced international dancing from 8 to 
10:45 p.m. Cost $2. (213) 392-3452. Gypsy Camp -- Friday nights. 3265 Motor 
Ave., West Los Angeles. Beginners class in Romanian dancing from 8:30 to 9:30 
p.m. Open international dancing from 9:30 to midnight. Cost: $6 with class, $5 
without class. (213) 558-0746. 
</P>
<P>
Kypseli -- Friday nights. 2031 Villa St., Pasadena. Class in Greek dancing from 
8 to 9 p.m. Open dancing from 9 to midnight. Cost: $4 with class, $3 without 
class. (213) 660-1030 or (818) 248-2020. Crestwood Folk Dancers -- Monday 
nights. Brockton School, 1309 Armacost Ave., West Los Angeles. Beginners class 
in international dancing from 7 to 8:15 p.m. Intermediate international dancing 
from 8:15 to 10:30 p.m. Call teacher Beverly Barr for class fees and locations 
of other classes. (213) 202-6166. 
</P>
<P>
Cafe Danssa -- Tuesday through Sunday nights. 11533 W. Pico Blvd., West Los 
Angeles. International dancing Friday; Israeli dancing Tuesday, Thursday, 
Saturday and Sunday. Open dancing 9:30 p.m. to midnight, often later. Lessons 8 
to 9:30 p.m.; telephone for class schedule. Balkan dancing Wednesday, 7:30 to 
11 p.m. Admission: $6; lessons 50 cents (buy one lesson, get the second free). 
(213) 478-7866, (213) 478-9960. 
</P>
<P>
Caltech International Folk Dancers -- Tuesday nights. Dabney Hall, Caltech 
Campus, 1201 E. California Blvd., Pasadena. Beginners class in international 
dancing from 7:30 to 8 p.m. Intermediate international dancing from 8 to 9 p.m. 
Open international dancing from 9 to midnight. Donations accepted. (213) 
849-2095 or (213) 261-3292. 
</P>
<P>
Folkdance with Mario Casetta -- Wednesday nights. 3131 S. Figueroa St., Los 
Angeles. Beginners class in international dancing from 7:30 to 9 p.m. Potluck 
party. Open international dancing from 9 to 10:30 p.m. Cost: $3.50. (213) 
666-6393 or (213) 743-5252. Specializes in beginners. 
</P>
<P>
Hollywood Peasants -- Wednesday nights. Plummer Park, 1200 N. Vista St., West 
Hollywood. Intermediate and advanced international dancing from 7:30 to 10 p.m. 
$1.50 donation. (213) 836-3069 or (213) 397-8110. 
</P>
<P>
Narodni Folk Dancers -- Thursday nights. Long Beach Unitarian Church, 5450 
Atherton St., Long Beach. Warm-up dancing from 7:30 to 8 p.m. Short 
beginner-intermediate class 8 p.m. Open international dancing, by request, from 
9 to 10:30 p.m. Cost: $2. (714) 897-2356 or (213) 421-9105. 
</P>
<P>
Royal Scottish Country Dancing Society -- Friday nights. El Retiro Park, 126 
Vista Del Parque, Torrance. Beginners class in Royal Scottish Country dancing 
from 7 to 8 p.m., intermediate and advanced Scottish dancing from 8 to 10 p.m. 
Cost: $3 per class. (213) 377-1675 or (213) 546-2005. Call for locations of 
other classes. 
</P>
<P>
Tuesday Gypsies -- Tuesday nights. Felicia Mahood Center, 11338 Santa Monica 
Blvd., West Los Angeles, 7:30-10 p.m. Intermediate international dancing. Cost: 
$3. (213) 556-3791. 
</P>
<P>
For information about other groups, call Beverly Barr, Folk Dance Federation of 
California South, (213) 202-6166. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, As these flying feet show, folk dancing is a fun exercise. JAMES 
RUEBSAMEN; Photo, Miriam Bitton and Haviv Israeli practice to perfect a new 
folk dance routine at a Westside club. ; Photo, At Cafe Danssa, above, 
instructors Dani Dassa and his daughter Dorite give a lesson early in the 
evening. All of the clubs offer such lessons. Afterward, everybody gets into 
the act, below. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
