<HEADLINE>
<P>
BLOW TO EMIGRES FROM E. EUROPE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Bush Administration on Wednesday virtually cut off the prospects for most 
Polish and Hungarian refugees in Western Europe to resettle in the United 
States any time soon. 
</P>
<P>
Citing "the democratic evolution" in those nations, the State Department said 
it will process no new applications by Polish and Hungarian refugees. 
</P>
<P>
Further, officials said, about 19,000 of the 20,000 applications on file likely 
will be rejected, because, with a few exceptions, only refugees with strong 
family ties in the United States will be admitted. 
</P>
<P>
The 20,000 applicants are but a fraction of the Polish and Hungarian refugee 
population in West Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
