<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. JOYCE BROTHERS: A DOG FOR DAD? ASK HIM FIRST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JOYCE BROTHERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: My father, who's 75, always wanted a pet, but my mother was 
allergic so they never had one during their marriage. Unfortunately, my mother 
died six months ago, and my father is having a difficult time adjusting. My 
husband and I are wondering about buying him a dog. Is this a good idea? 
</P>
<P>
 -- B.L. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR B.L.: It might be great, but I certainly wouldn't do anything until you've 
talked it over with him first. It's important to find out if he can have a pet 
where he lives and also to consider if he's able to give an animal the care and 
attention it needs. 
</P>
<P>
Having a dog is a responsibility, as well as a joy. Just as with humans, it 
takes time for relationships to build. Puppies always need to be housebroken. 
Even well-trained, older dogs may make mistakes for the first night or two 
while getting adjusted to a new person and a new home. 
</P>
<P>
If your father is able to walk the dog, this would probably be good for him, as 
well as for the animal. It would get him out of the house and give him a new 
interest. You might want to think about getting an older dog, one who's gentle 
and trained and one whose disposition and temperament would blend well with 
your father. 
</P>
<P>
Studies show that good pets help to alleviate loneliness, and stroking pets can 
lower the blood pressure. If your father is contemplating a move, however, it 
might be better to wait until he's settled. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: I think my 34-year-old son is making a terrible mistake, but 
there's not much use of my talking to him because he never listens to his 
father. He's about to pass up a promotion in order to have more time to stay at 
home with his two children. He tells me this isn't as unusual as it was in my 
day. It seems absurd to me. This isn't a man's role. He has a wife, and even 
though she works, it seems to me he's trying to do her job. 
</P>
<P>
 -- L.C. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR L.C.: Your son is correct when he reports that more and more young fathers 
are choosing to be good fathers first and are placing their families ahead of 
their jobs. Many of these men do this because they feel they didn't get to see 
enough of their own fathers in their childhood and are determined to be closer 
to their children than their fathers were to them. 
</P>
<P>
There's no question about it, we're living through a social revolution when it 
comes to sex roles. Men used to define themselves and their role in society as 
the breadwinner, but men are no longer the only breadwinners. Many children are 
being raised in two-career families, such as your son's, and when this is the 
case, both partners frequently find themselves making some sacrifices in 
furthering their careers in order to be better parents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
