<HEADLINE>
<P>
SPILLING THE BEANS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: Only a short while ago I never would have believed some of the foods 
that are being recommended today as part of a healthy diet. I always used to 
think that pasta and potatoes had to be avoided, but now I can understand that 
these are nutritious foods. Now I see that beans have become a kind of glamour 
food. Is this just a fad, or do beans belong in the average diet? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Beans are a nutritious food that have the added advantage of providing 
a great deal of fiber. They also lend themselves to being served in combination 
with a variety of animal foods, such as meat, fish, poultry, eggs, milk and 
cheese, as well as with non-animal foods, such as peas and lentils. These 
combinations provide a complete protein. 
</P>
<P>
Still another advantage is that beans are an economical food, a consideration 
that cannot be ignored. Furthermore, they do not contain unwanted fat or salt. 
</P>
<P>
One of the criticisms often heard about beans is that they cause gas. While 
this is true, this effect can be reduced by adding beans to the diet gradually, 
as well as by the manner in which they are prepared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA112389-0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 138991 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 23, 1989, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
