<HEADLINE>
<P>
NIBBLES AND BITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Kenneth Williams 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Westlake Village-based television production company's plans to convert one 
of Anaheim's original luxury movie houses into a TV studio have collapsed. 
Complying with myriad requirements of Anaheim city officials -- from widening 
sidewalks to redesigning a driveway -- proved impossible for Winning 
Productions, said spokesman Matt Cimber. The production firm had signed a lease 
to turn the decaying Cinemaland theater into a studio where game shows and 
other programs would have been produced before live audiences. While Winning 
was ready to fund the theater's conversion and refurbishment, "We were not 
about to start redesigning Anaheim," Cimber said. There are currently no 
alternative plans for the landmark cinema across the street from Disneyland, a 
city official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA112389-0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 139193 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 23, 1989, Thursday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
